<DOC><DOCNO> AP880912-0235 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1034EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f PM-Macmillan     09-12 0343</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Macmillan,0359</SECOND><HEAD>URGENT</HEAD><HEAD>Book Publisher Agrees to Buyout By New York Investment Firm</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Publishing giant Macmillan Inc., target ofunwanted takeover offers for four months, said today that it willbe bought by the investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts andamp; Co. in acash deal that values the company at $2.36 billion.   The announcement came after reports surfaced that Macmillanofficials had negotiated this weekend with Kohlberg Kravis, aprivate partnership that has helped other large companies thwartunwelcome takeovers.   Kohlberg Kravis specializes in leveraged buyouts, in which acompany is acquired through mostly borrowed money repaid from thetarget company's profits or asset sales.   Macmillan said in a brief announcement that Kolhberg Kravis hadformed a subsidiary to begin a tender offer of $85 cash per sharefor up to 26.1 million shares of the company, or 94 percent of thetotal. The offer values the company's 27.76 million shares at about$2.36 billion.   The announcement was the latest twist in a takeover battle wagedsince May for Macmillan, a large New York-based publishing concernand leading supplier of college textbooks. The company owns otheroperations that range from the Berlitz foreign language trainingprogram to Katharine Gibbs clerical schools.   A group headed by British publisher Robert Maxwell had beenattempting to buy Macmillan and last week offered to raise its$80-a-share offer to $84 a share. A group headed by Texas investorRobert Bass has offered $75 a share.   The company had spurned offers from both and sought torestructure itself to thwart a takeover by selling the informationdivision.   The Bass group, which owns about 9.2 percent of Macmillan'sshares, had successfully challenged the move in court, but thecompany said today that because of the planned acquisition byKohlberg Kravis it is scrapping the restructuring plan.   Rumors that Macmillan had enlisted the help of Kohlberg Kravishelped boost the price of the company's stock Friday by $3.62{ to$83.87{ in composite New York Stock Exchange trading.   In early trading today Macmillan rose to $84.62{.</TEXT></DOC>